Anonymous Wed 07 Feb 2018 00:21:53 No.13903978 Report
Quoted By: >>13904042
>>13903762
Well, the Falcon Heavy can shunt a little under 64,000 kilos into a low orbit, while the Saturn V could get 140,000 kg to the same height.
The Saturn V, which was optimized for the single purpose of going to the Moon, could only put 48,600 kg into a lunar insertion orbit. The Falcon Heavy is more general purpose, so it should have a bigger falloff, which in the SpaceX figures is the case - they only indicated getting about a quarter of the LEO payload into a lunar insertion orbit, while Saturn V could get just over a third of its LEO cargo to LIO. The Delta-v from earth escape to land on Mars is considerably more punishing than to the moon for obvious reasons, so I wouldn't expect the Falcon Heavy to be remotely useful for a Mars shot.

The BFR is intended to have a LEO payload of 150,000 kg, and NASA's SLS likewise is targeting up to 130,000 kg, and both are being designed as Moon vehicles. As far as I remember, neither of them is meant to be a viable Mars rocket for a manned mission by themselves, but rather could serve as a design platform for things that could go interplanetary.
